# Read in data files 
cranes_df = read_csv("Cranes.csv")

# Create data 
waggle_df = tibble("Distance" = c(200, 250, 500, 950, 1950, 3500, 4300), "Duration" = c(.40, .45, .95, 1.30, 2.00, 3.10, 4.10))

Problem 1: Honeybee Waggle Dance

(a) Create an appropriate scatterplot.

# Create Scatterplot
ggplot(waggle_df, aes(x=Duration, y=Distance)) + 
  geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Honeybee's 'Waggle Dance' in Duration to Distance") +
  xlab("Duration (Seconds)") + 
  ylab("Distance (Meters)") +
  # Themes
  scale_colour_viridis_d() + 
  # Theme
  theme(
    # hide panel borders and remove grid lines
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
    panel.border = element_blank(), 
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(), 
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    # change axis titles 
    axis.line = element_line(color = "black"),
    axis.title = element_text(size=11),
    # Change the title orientation 
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)
  )

There is a strong positive linear relationship between a Honeybees Waggle Dance duration and the distance from the food source.

(b) Report the correlation coefficient between duration and distance.

The correlation between the duration of the Waggle Dance and the distance from the food source is: 0.994

(c) Find the equation of the least squares line and write the equation using variable names.

m <- lm(Distance ~ Duration, data=waggle_df)
sm <- summary(m)

The linear model is appropriate to be used with these data, the model is not overfitted and the residuals are evenly distributed.

(e) Interpret the slope of the regression line. (coef(m)[2]) in the context of the problem.

The slope of the regression line fit to these data predicts that for every additional second elapsed in a honeybees Waggle Dance, the distance from the food source would increase by 1174.2576061 meters.

(d) Report and interpret the values of \(R^2\) and \(s_e\).

The \(R^2\) value represents the variation accounted for by the model. \(R^2\): 0.988. This means that 98.8% of variation in the distance from the food source is explained by the duration of the Bees Waggle Dance.

The \(s_e\) value is 194.924 which indicates that the predictions from this model are expected to be off by about 194.924 meters on average of Bees Waggle Dances from the same population.

(c) Fit the linear model for predicting log10(Count) from year. Report only the intercept and slope of the model.

# Create Linear model for prediction log10(Count) from year
c_m <- lm(log10(Count) ~ Year, data=cranes_df)
c_sm <- summary(c_m)

The intercept of the linear regression model is -31.877, where the coefficient is 0.017. The predicted Whooping Crane population in the Aransas National Wildlife Refuge in Texas would increase by 4.0076615% for every additional year.

The equation of the linear regression model is as follows. \[ \widehat {Log_{10}(Count-of-Whooping-Cranes)} = -31.877 + 0.017\,(Year) \]

(d) Whats the predicted number of cranes from your model for 2020 and 2050?

The predicted number of Whooping Cranes in the Aransas National Wildlife Refuge for the following years would be:

  • 2020: 393.339 Whooping Cranes

  • 2050: 1278.577 Whooping Cranes
